<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/loose.dtd"><html>

<head>

<title>UPDATE-PATCH-COLOUR</title>

</head>

<body>
	<h3><i>Each patch of the Sugarscape repeatedly compute their colour depending 

	upon how much sugar has accumulated.</i> </h3>

	<font size="2" color="gray">Begin micro-behaviour</font>
	<p><b>UPDATE-PATCH-COLOUR </b></p>

	<font size="2" color="gray">Begin NetLogo code:</font>
	<pre>do-every 1
   [ask-every-patch
        [set pcolor 49 - sugar-of-patch]]
</pre>

	<font size="2" color="gray">End NetLogo code</font>
	<h2>Variants</h2>

	<p>You could use the colour to depict other attributes or use a different 

	colour scheme. </p>

	<h2>Related Micro-behaviours</h2>


	<p>

	<a title="GROW-SUGAR-DELAYED" href="GROW-SUGAR-DELAYED.html">

	GROW-SUGAR-DELAYED</a> is the process that updates the accumulated sugar of 

	each patch. </p>

	<h2>How this works</h2>

	<p>In

	<a target="_blank" class="external text" title="http://ccl.northwestern.edu/netlogo/docs/programming.html#colors" rel="nofollow" href="http://ccl.northwestern.edu/netlogo/docs/programming.html#colors">

	NetLogo's colour scheme</a> yellow is represented by the number 45. Lighter 

	shades of yellow range between 45 and 49. On every <i>tick</i> every 

	patch sets it colour to a shade of yellow. This code assumes that 

	accumulated sugar ranges from 0 to 4. </p>

	<h2>Source</h2>
	<p>Based upon page 21 of [1]. </p>

	<h2>History</h2>



	<p>This was implemented by Ken Kahn. </p>

	<h2>References</h2>

	<p>[1] <i>Growing Artificial Societies</i> by Joshua M. Epstein and Robert 

	Axtell, Brookings Institute Press, The MIT Press, 1996. </p>

</body>
